# UPDATE Commands

### Update Single Column

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = value
WHERE condition;
```

### Update Multiple Columns

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column1 = value1,
    column2 = value2
WHERE condition;
```

### Update All Rows

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = value;
```

### Update Using Expression

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = column_name + value
WHERE condition;
```

### Update Using Subquery

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = value
WHERE column_name =
(
    SELECT column_name
    FROM table_name
);
```
Group By  AND Having cause

Group By =In a GROUP BY query, only the column(s) specified in the GROUP BY clause have the same value within each group. Other columns may contain different values unless they are also included in the GROUP BY clause or used inside aggregate functions like COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(), MIN(), or MAX()

ex = Example Table
id	name	dept_id	salary
1	Lalit	1	50000
2	Rahul	1	60000
3	Amit	2	70000
4	Mohan	2	80000

Query = SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*)
FROM Employee
GROUP BY dept_id;

Final Output

dept_id	COUNT(*)
1	     2
2	     2

Having = HAVING is used to filter groups created by GROUP BY

ex= SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) 
FROM Employee 
GROUP BY dept_id 
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1

